// stdlib/kernels/orbital/kepler_2body_kernel.hexa — D80 g_hexa_only
// pilot (demiurge AGENTS.tape @D g_hexa_only — ultimate form).
//
// One of the D80 g_hexa_only pilots — following the same provenance
// + parity template as `stdlib/kernels/solar/solar_kernel.hexa`,
// `stdlib/kernels/mc_transport/mc_slab_demo.hexa`,
// `stdlib/kernels/graph/bfs_topo_kernel.hexa`,
// `stdlib/kernels/neural/lif_kernel.hexa`, and
// `stdlib/kernels/urdf/fk_2link_kernel.hexa`. Clean-room
// hexa-native Kepler two-body closed-form propagator: given a
// central-body GM, an orbit's semi-major axis + eccentricity, and a
// time since periapsis, solve Kepler's equation by Newton–Raphson
// (5 steps suffice to machine precision for e ≤ 0.7) and reduce to
// in-plane cartesian coordinates.
//
// Layer (ABSORPTION.md ① / demiurge design.md D72):
//   ①a kernel — THIS FILE. Domain-agnostic. No TLE, no NORAD set,
//                no ground observer, no SGP4 perturbations — pure
//                "given (μ, a, e, t) over a Kepler two-body, where
//                is the body in its orbital plane".
//   ①b adapter — none yet for the 2-body closed-form. The existing
//                SGP4 propagator (`sgp4_kernel.py` + Skyfield) stays
//                the ①a kernel for FULL satellite propagation
//                (J2/drag/lunar); the day a hexa-native SGP4 port
//                lands, this 2-body kernel becomes its inner closed-
//                form solver (an SGP4 mean-element step is, modulo
//                perturbations, a Kepler equation solve per epoch).
//
// @version 0.1.0
// @capabilities [pure]
// @stability stage-2 substrate (clean-room re-derivation, no poliastro
//   or astropy call). Substrate parity against Python's `math` library
//   reference (numpy 2.0, Python 3.x on darwin-arm64) verified by
//   `kepler_2body_kernel_test.hexa` for 5 timesteps × 5 eccentricities
//   over (a=7000 km LEO, GM_earth) to <1e-12 relative on E / ν / r /
//   x / y (well inside the 1e-10 D80 tolerance ceiling).
// @since 2026-05-20
//
// CLEAN-ROOM PROVENANCE
//   This module carries NO poliastro / astropy / spice code — it
//   implements the textbook Kepler equation closed-form directly
//   from Vallado "Fundamentals of Astrodynamics and Applications"
//   (4th ed., 2013) §2.2 and Curtis "Orbital Mechanics for
//   Engineering Students" (3rd ed., 2014) §3.6. Both algorithms are
//   mathematical-fact closed-form expressions; no proprietary or
//   copyrighted source.
//
//   - upstream code   : none (clean-room re-derivation)
//   - upstream spec   : J.Kepler, "Astronomia Nova" (1609); Newton-
//                       Raphson iteration on M = E − e·sin(E)
//                       (textbook standard).
//                       Vallado, Algorithm 2 (Kepler's Eq, NR), p.65.
//                       Curtis, §3.6 (true anomaly from E), p.149.
//   - parity baseline : Python `math` (libm) closed-form on
//                       darwin-arm64, Python 3.x, numpy 2.0.
//
// HONESTY (g3 — non-negotiable, inherited by every caller):
//   * Computed (E, ν, r, x, y) IS the algorithm output — both sides
//     run the SAME closed-form Newton-Raphson Kepler solve in IEEE-
//     754 double precision; given identical (μ, a, e, t) they MUST
//     agree to last-bit-of-double across hosts. The parity test
//     asserts <1e-12 relative.
//   * BUT the two-body Kepler model assumes a POINT-MASS central
//     body and no perturbations — for a real satellite around Earth,
//     J2 oblateness (~1 km/orbit drift), atmospheric drag (LEO),
//     lunar/solar third-body (GEO+) and solar radiation pressure
//     (high-area-to-mass) all matter. SGP4 (the current
//     `sgp4_kernel.py`) bundles those perturbations. This kernel is
//     the *unperturbed* baseline — useful for synthetic tests,
//     mission design at coarse altitude, and as the inner solve for
//     a future hexa-native SGP4 port.
//   * Parabolic (e=1) and hyperbolic (e>1) orbits are NOT in scope
//     — Newton-Raphson on M=E−e·sin(E) only converges for elliptical
//     orbits (0 ≤ e < 1). Hyperbolic Kepler equation uses
//     M=e·sinh(F)−F (a separate solve, a separate kernel). The
//     kernel returns NaN-like sentinel behavior outside [0, 1); the
//     ①b adapter must gate.
//   * Substrate parity (`kepler_2body_kernel_test.hexa`) only proves
//     the PORT PATTERN — D80's record-layer `absorbed=true` flip
//     needs the demiurge HexaNativeParityRef schema + a measured
//     ephemeris oracle (out of scope here per g3).
//
// Surface (all SI; angles in radians; in-plane cartesian):
//   pub fn kepler_solve_E(M: float, ecc: float, n_iters: int) -> float
//   pub fn mean_anomaly(mu: float, a: float, t: float) -> float
//   pub fn true_anomaly(E: float, ecc: float) -> float
//   pub fn radius(a: float, ecc: float, E: float) -> float
//   pub fn propagate(mu, a, ecc, t) -> [E, nu, r, x, y]   (5-float array)
//
// NOTE on parameter name: the stdlib `math/float` module exports a
// constant function `e()` (Euler's number); we use `ecc` for the
// eccentricity to avoid the codegen treating a bare identifier `e`
// as a function reference.

use "stdlib/core/math/float"

// ── helpers ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

/// Reduce angle (rad) to (-π, π]. The 2-body closed-form is invariant
/// under M → M ± 2π·k, but Newton-Raphson from E₀ = M converges
/// fastest when |M| ≤ π. Implemented as a `fmod(x, 2π)`-style reduce
/// into [0, 2π) followed by a single shift if > π — this lands in
/// (-π, π], matching Python's `fmod`-based convention at the +π
/// boundary (rather than the alternative `floor((x+π)/2π)`
/// formulation, which would map +π → −π and disagree on the
/// representative at apoapsis).
fn wrap_pi(x: float) -> float {
    let two_pi = 2.0 * pi()
    // Reduce into [0, 2π) via `x − 2π·floor(x/2π)` (mathematical
    // floored-modulo — works for negative x too).
    let mut m = x - two_pi * floor(x / two_pi)
    // Now shift (π, 2π) → (−π, 0). Note `>` not `≥` — exact +π stays
    // at +π (matches Python `fmod` + post-shift convention).
    if m > pi() { m = m - two_pi }
    return m
}

// ── Kepler equation solve ────────────────────────────────────────────

/// Newton-Raphson solve of Kepler's equation M = E − e·sin(E).
/// Returns E (rad).
///
///   f(E)   = E − e·sin(E) − M
///   f'(E)  = 1 − e·cos(E)
///   E_{k+1} = E_k − f(E_k) / f'(E_k)
///
/// Initial guess E₀ = M (good for moderate e; for e > 0.8 a better
/// seed like E₀ = M + e·sin(M) speeds convergence — but at 5 NR steps
/// the simple seed already saturates double precision for e ≤ 0.7,
/// verified by `kepler_2body_kernel_test.hexa`).
///
/// Domain: 0 ≤ e < 1 (elliptical). For e=1 (parabolic) or e>1
/// (hyperbolic) the iteration may stall or diverge — the kernel does
/// NOT guard (callers / ①b adapters own the eccentricity gate).
///
/// `n_iters` fixed-count loop (no convergence test) — 5 steps suffice
/// to <1e-15 relative for e ≤ 0.7 starting from E₀=M, due to NR's
/// quadratic convergence (one good step ≈ doubles correct digits).
pub fn kepler_solve_E(M: float, ecc: float, n_iters: int) -> float {
    let M_wrapped = wrap_pi(M)
    let mut E = M_wrapped
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n_iters {
        let f  = E - ecc * sin(E) - M_wrapped
        let fp = 1.0 - ecc * cos(E)
        E = E - f / fp
        i = i + 1
    }
    return E
}

// ── orbital-element conversions ──────────────────────────────────────

/// Mean anomaly M (rad) at time t (s) since periapsis, given μ (m³/s²)
/// and semi-major axis a (m).
///   n = sqrt(μ / a³)      (mean motion, rad/s)
///   M = n · t              (unwrapped)
///
/// Caller may pass the unwrapped value into `kepler_solve_E` — that
/// function wraps internally.
pub fn mean_anomaly(mu: float, a: float, t: float) -> float {
    let n = sqrt(mu / (a * a * a))
    return n * t
}

/// True anomaly ν (rad) from eccentric anomaly E and eccentricity e.
/// Standard half-angle identity (Vallado eq. 2-14, Curtis 3.13b):
///   tan(ν/2) = sqrt((1+e)/(1−e)) · tan(E/2)
/// Implemented via atan2 to keep the quadrant correct in (-π, π].
///
///   ν = 2 · atan2(sqrt(1+e)·sin(E/2),
///                 sqrt(1−e)·cos(E/2))
pub fn true_anomaly(E: float, ecc: float) -> float {
    let half_E = 0.5 * E
    let s = sqrt(1.0 + ecc) * sin(half_E)
    let c = sqrt(1.0 - ecc) * cos(half_E)
    return 2.0 * atan2(s, c)
}

/// Orbital radius r (m) from semi-major axis a (m), eccentricity e,
/// and eccentric anomaly E (rad):
///   r = a · (1 − e·cos(E))
/// (Vallado eq. 2-13.)
pub fn radius(a: float, ecc: float, E: float) -> float {
    return a * (1.0 - ecc * cos(E))
}

// ── full propagator ──────────────────────────────────────────────────

/// Closed-form Kepler 2-body propagation. Returns 5 doubles packed in
/// a fixed-length array:
///   [E_rad, nu_rad, r_m, x_m, y_m]
/// where (x, y) are in-plane cartesian with the focus at the origin
/// and periapsis on the +x axis (standard perifocal frame, P-Q plane
/// per Vallado Fig.2-6).
///
/// Inputs:
///   mu — central-body gravitational parameter GM (m³/s²)
///   a  — semi-major axis (m, > 0)
///   e  — eccentricity (0 ≤ e < 1, elliptical only)
///   t  — time since periapsis (s; may be negative or > orbital period
///        — the kernel wraps via wrap_pi internally)
///
/// Uses a fixed 5-step Newton-Raphson — sufficient to <1e-12 relative
/// across the test grid (5 timesteps × 5 eccentricities up to e=0.7);
/// see `kepler_2body_kernel_test.hexa`.
pub fn propagate(mu: float, a: float, ecc: float, t: float) -> [float] {
    let M  = mean_anomaly(mu, a, t)
    let E  = kepler_solve_E(M, ecc, 5)
    let nu = true_anomaly(E, ecc)
    let r  = radius(a, ecc, E)
    let x  = r * cos(nu)
    let y  = r * sin(nu)
    return [E, nu, r, x, y]
}

// ── ①b adapter note ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// A future `stdlib/space/kepler_2body.hexa` ①b adapter would supply
// the central-body GM table (Earth / Moon / Mars / Sun / Jupiter),
// a periapsis epoch + inclination / RAAN / argument-of-periapsis
// rotation into the inertial frame, and the honesty caveats for
// THAT specific orbit (J2 ignored, drag ignored, ...). This kernel
// only ports the closed-form 2-body math (Kepler solve + perifocal
// reduction); inclination / RAAN / ω rotation into ECI is the
// adapter layer's responsibility (3 cheap rotation matrices).
//
// A future hexa-native SGP4 port would call this kernel as its inner
// closed-form step (SGP4 mean-element propagation = Kepler equation
// solve per epoch, modulo the J2 / drag / lunar perturbation series).
